selector_to_html = {"a[href=\"#introduction\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Introduction<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#introduction\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h2><p>When you\u2019re working on large-scale single-cell datasets, you should manually collect metadata for each study. Here are some benefits:</p>", "a[href=\"#study-metadata\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Study metadata<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#study-metadata\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h2><h3>Study name &amp; Sample name<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#study-name-sample-name\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h3><p>Usually, we define the study as one publication conducted by one lab. Samples in the same study usually compareble. For example, the paper <a class=\"reference external\" href=\"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-022-32490-y\"><strong>Spatiotemporal single-cell regulatory atlas reveals neural crest lineage diversification and cellular function during tooth morphogenesis</strong></a> <span id=\"id1\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id2\" title=\"Junjun Jing, Jifan Feng, Yuan Yuan, Tingwei Guo, Jie Lei, Fei Pei, Thach-Vu Ho, and Yang Chai. Spatiotemporal single-cell regulatory atlas reveals neural crest lineage diversification and cellular function during tooth morphogenesis. Nature Communications, 13(1):4803, August 2022. doi:10.1038/s41467-022-32490-y.\">Jing <em>et al.</em>, 2022</a>]</span> conducted by Yang Chai lab contains five samples ranges from E13.5 to PN7.5 in mouse embyro development. In my convention, I use characters \u201cuniqueID+author\u201d to name the study and use \u201cuniqueID+sampleName\u201d to name the sample. In this example, the study name is <code class=\"docutils literal notranslate\"><span class=\"pre\">ToothNc_Junjun</span></code> and the sample name is <code class=\"docutils literal notranslate\"><span class=\"pre\">ToothNc_Junjun_E13.5</span></code>. The most important thing is the study name should be easy to remember and unique.</p>", "a[href=\"#tissue-information\"]": "<h3 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Tissue information<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#tissue-information\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h3><p>This is the most tricky part, and it is highly dependent on your purpose. For example, when I build the <a class=\"reference external\" href=\"https://trajatlas.readthedocs.io/en/stable/introduction/Differentiation_Atlas.html\">Differentiation Atlas</a> focus on bone development, I found it\u2019s hard to use one single tissue information to summarize the tissue information. So I use multi-level tissue information for description. Some reviews <span id=\"id2\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id3\" title=\"Toshihide Mizoguchi and Noriaki Ono. The diverse origin of bone-forming osteoblasts. Journal of Bone and Mineral Research, 36(8):1432\u20131447, 2021. doi:10.1002/jbmr.4410.\">Mizoguchi and Ono, 2021</a>]</span> suggests there are three main organs that generated the osteoblasts: Head, Limb bud and Long bone, and the osteogenic pathways are significantly different across the organs. So I used <strong>tissue origin</strong> which contains these three categories to describe the main organ sources. And in a finer resolution, we can see that the organ can be divided into the <strong>histological</strong> and <strong>tissue location</strong> subtypes <span id=\"id3\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id4\" title=\"Hui Sophie Shu, Yiming Liam Liu, Xinyu Thomas Tang, Xinyi Shirley Zhang, Bin Zhou, Weiguo Zou, and Bo O. Zhou. Tracing the skeletal progenitor transition during postnatal bone formation. Cell Stem Cell, 28(12):2122-2136.e3, December 2021. doi:10.1016/j.stem.2021.08.010.\">Shu <em>et al.</em>, 2021</a>]</span>. For example, the long bone can be divided into metaphysis, diaphysis, and epiphysis, which is histologically different. And it can also be divided into tibia, fumer, which is location different. Therefore, I finally form three-level tissue metadata.\n<img alt=\"png\" src=\"../_images/meta_tissue.png\"/></p><p>And in the tooth development the situation is completely different. First, the tooth from <strong>mandibular or maxillary</strong> may have great shape and transcriptional difference <span id=\"id4\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id5\" title=\"Thira Faruangsaeng, Sermporn Thaweesapphitak, Chompak Khamwachirapitak, Thantrira Porntaveetus, and Vorasuk Shotelersuk. Comparative transcriptome profiles of human dental pulp stem cells from maxillary and mandibular teeth. Scientific Reports, 12:8860, May 2022. doi:10.1038/s41598-022-12867-1.\">Faruangsaeng <em>et al.</em>, 2022</a>]</span> <span id=\"id5\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id6\" title=\"Sophie Pantalacci, Laurent Gu\u00e9guen, Coraline Petit, Anne Lambert, Renata Peterkov\u00e0, and Marie S\u00e9mon. Transcriptomic signatures shaped by cell proportions shed light on comparative developmental biology. Genome Biology, 18:29, February 2017. doi:10.1186/s13059-017-1157-7.\">Pantalacci <em>et al.</em>, 2017</a>]</span>. This is significant in mouse, as the mandibular incisors of mice are longer than maxillary incisors.\n<img alt=\"png\" src=\"../_images/meta_tissue_tooth.png\"/>\nEven more significant is the distinction between tooth types. The differences between molars and incisors extend beyond shape to include enamel structure. In incisors, the enamel exhibits a uniserial lamellar pattern of prisms in the inner enamel, while the outer enamel features parallel radial prisms. In contrast, molars display a multifaceted rod pattern with more variable structures than those found in incisors.\n<img alt=\"Enamel Structure Differences\" src=\"../_images/20241023_enamel.png\"/>\n{:.image-caption}\n<em>The caption for my image</em></p>", "a[href=\"#biological-covariates\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Biological covariates<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#biological-covariates\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h2><h3>Tissue information<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#tissue-information\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h3><p>This is the most tricky part, and it is highly dependent on your purpose. For example, when I build the <a class=\"reference external\" href=\"https://trajatlas.readthedocs.io/en/stable/introduction/Differentiation_Atlas.html\">Differentiation Atlas</a> focus on bone development, I found it\u2019s hard to use one single tissue information to summarize the tissue information. So I use multi-level tissue information for description. Some reviews <span id=\"id2\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id3\" title=\"Toshihide Mizoguchi and Noriaki Ono. The diverse origin of bone-forming osteoblasts. Journal of Bone and Mineral Research, 36(8):1432\u20131447, 2021. doi:10.1002/jbmr.4410.\">Mizoguchi and Ono, 2021</a>]</span> suggests there are three main organs that generated the osteoblasts: Head, Limb bud and Long bone, and the osteogenic pathways are significantly different across the organs. So I used <strong>tissue origin</strong> which contains these three categories to describe the main organ sources. And in a finer resolution, we can see that the organ can be divided into the <strong>histological</strong> and <strong>tissue location</strong> subtypes <span id=\"id3\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id4\" title=\"Hui Sophie Shu, Yiming Liam Liu, Xinyu Thomas Tang, Xinyi Shirley Zhang, Bin Zhou, Weiguo Zou, and Bo O. Zhou. Tracing the skeletal progenitor transition during postnatal bone formation. Cell Stem Cell, 28(12):2122-2136.e3, December 2021. doi:10.1016/j.stem.2021.08.010.\">Shu <em>et al.</em>, 2021</a>]</span>. For example, the long bone can be divided into metaphysis, diaphysis, and epiphysis, which is histologically different. And it can also be divided into tibia, fumer, which is location different. Therefore, I finally form three-level tissue metadata.\n<img alt=\"png\" src=\"../_images/meta_tissue.png\"/></p><p>And in the tooth development the situation is completely different. First, the tooth from <strong>mandibular or maxillary</strong> may have great shape and transcriptional difference <span id=\"id4\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id5\" title=\"Thira Faruangsaeng, Sermporn Thaweesapphitak, Chompak Khamwachirapitak, Thantrira Porntaveetus, and Vorasuk Shotelersuk. Comparative transcriptome profiles of human dental pulp stem cells from maxillary and mandibular teeth. Scientific Reports, 12:8860, May 2022. doi:10.1038/s41598-022-12867-1.\">Faruangsaeng <em>et al.</em>, 2022</a>]</span> <span id=\"id5\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id6\" title=\"Sophie Pantalacci, Laurent Gu\u00e9guen, Coraline Petit, Anne Lambert, Renata Peterkov\u00e0, and Marie S\u00e9mon. Transcriptomic signatures shaped by cell proportions shed light on comparative developmental biology. Genome Biology, 18:29, February 2017. doi:10.1186/s13059-017-1157-7.\">Pantalacci <em>et al.</em>, 2017</a>]</span>. This is significant in mouse, as the mandibular incisors of mice are longer than maxillary incisors.\n<img alt=\"png\" src=\"../_images/meta_tissue_tooth.png\"/>\nEven more significant is the distinction between tooth types. The differences between molars and incisors extend beyond shape to include enamel structure. In incisors, the enamel exhibits a uniserial lamellar pattern of prisms in the inner enamel, while the outer enamel features parallel radial prisms. In contrast, molars display a multifaceted rod pattern with more variable structures than those found in incisors.\n<img alt=\"Enamel Structure Differences\" src=\"../_images/20241023_enamel.png\"/>\n{:.image-caption}\n<em>The caption for my image</em></p>", "a[href=\"#metadata-collection\"]": "<h1 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Metadata Collection<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#metadata-collection\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h1><h2>Introduction<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#introduction\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h2><p>When you\u2019re working on large-scale single-cell datasets, you should manually collect metadata for each study. Here are some benefits:</p>", "a[href=\"#data-accession\"]": "<h3 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Data accession<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#data-accession\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h3><p>This is the accession number of the data. For example, the data of <code class=\"docutils literal notranslate\"><span class=\"pre\">ToothNc_Junjun</span></code> is <a class=\"reference external\" href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE189381\">GSE189381</a>. Once you have recorded this information, you can easily access the data if you forget the data source.</p>", "a[href=\"#study-name-sample-name\"]": "<h3 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Study name &amp; Sample name<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#study-name-sample-name\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h3><p>Usually, we define the study as one publication conducted by one lab. Samples in the same study usually compareble. For example, the paper <a class=\"reference external\" href=\"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-022-32490-y\"><strong>Spatiotemporal single-cell regulatory atlas reveals neural crest lineage diversification and cellular function during tooth morphogenesis</strong></a> <span id=\"id1\">[<a class=\"reference internal\" href=\"../references.html#id2\" title=\"Junjun Jing, Jifan Feng, Yuan Yuan, Tingwei Guo, Jie Lei, Fei Pei, Thach-Vu Ho, and Yang Chai. Spatiotemporal single-cell regulatory atlas reveals neural crest lineage diversification and cellular function during tooth morphogenesis. Nature Communications, 13(1):4803, August 2022. doi:10.1038/s41467-022-32490-y.\">Jing <em>et al.</em>, 2022</a>]</span> conducted by Yang Chai lab contains five samples ranges from E13.5 to PN7.5 in mouse embyro development. In my convention, I use characters \u201cuniqueID+author\u201d to name the study and use \u201cuniqueID+sampleName\u201d to name the sample. In this example, the study name is <code class=\"docutils literal notranslate\"><span class=\"pre\">ToothNc_Junjun</span></code> and the sample name is <code class=\"docutils literal notranslate\"><span class=\"pre\">ToothNc_Junjun_E13.5</span></code>. The most important thing is the study name should be easy to remember and unique.</p>", "a[href=\"#what-metadata-to-collect\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">What metadata to collect?<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#what-metadata-to-collect\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">\u00b6</a></h2><p>While this is highly dependent on the study, here are some general categories of metadata that are often collected:</p>"}
skip_classes = ["headerlink", "sd-stretched-link"]

window.onload = function () {
    for (const [select, tip_html] of Object.entries(selector_to_html)) {
        const links = document.querySelectorAll(` ${select}`);
        for (const link of links) {
            if (skip_classes.some(c => link.classList.contains(c))) {
                continue;
            }

            tippy(link, {
                content: tip_html,
                allowHTML: true,
                arrow: true,
                placement: 'auto-start', maxWidth: 500, interactive: false,

            });
        };
    };
    console.log("tippy tips loaded!");
};
